{#
  newsletter.inky.twig — an inky template that is ALSO a real Twig template.

  Written for CMS integrators shipping inky inside a Twig-based CMS (e.g.
  Total CMS): this file mixes inky's own tags (<layout>, <container>,
  <raw>, ...) with real Twig syntax ({{ }}, {% %}, filters). There are two
  valid orders to combine them — see run.php, which builds both, times
  them, and asserts they agree for one recipient.

  ORDER A — Twig first, then inky (`Inky::build`, no `data` option). Twig
  renders the FULL document — substituting every {{ }} and expanding the
  {% for %} loop below — before inky ever sees it; inky then only does
  component transform, SCSS, and CSS inlining. Simple, always correct,
  but costs a full inky build PER RECIPIENT.

  ORDER B — inky first (the CMS fast path), then Twig per recipient.
  `Inky::build` runs ONCE, with no `data` option, on this raw file — all
  Twig syntax passes through untouched (inky's own MiniJinja merge step is
  simply skipped when `data` isn't passed; see 03-data-merge). That one
  build does layout/include resolution, component transform, and CSS
  inlining a single time, producing a "shell" that still contains literal
  Twig syntax — cache THAT instead of re-doing the inky build for every
  recipient. Twig then renders the cached shell per recipient, which is
  far cheaper than a full inky build per recipient. This is the shape a
  CMS wants: template content changes rarely, recipients don't.

  THE <raw> RULE — and here it stops being optional, unlike the
  defense-in-depth framing in 03-data-merge's comment. In Order B, the
  {% for %} loop below has NOT been expanded yet when inky's HTML5-based
  component transform runs over this file. A bare, un-wrapped
  {% for %}...{% endfor %} sitting directly inside <table> (outside any
  <tr>) is, as far as the HTML5 parser is concerned, stray non-table
  text — the spec's foster-parenting rule relocates it OUT of the table
  entirely, silently detaching the loop from the rows it's meant to
  produce and corrupting the newsletter for every recipient. (Order A
  never hits this: by the time inky sees the document, Twig has already
  expanded the loop into ordinary <tr> tags, which ARE valid table
  content and are never foster-parented.) <raw> sidesteps the problem
  because inky extracts <raw>...</raw> content BEFORE html5ever parses
  anything at all, replacing it with an HTML COMMENT placeholder —
  comments, unlike bare text, are legal directly inside <table>, so the
  placeholder survives parsing exactly where it was, and the real
  (untouched) content is spliced back in afterward. One thing NOT to draw
  from this: <raw> content is re-injected before CSS inlining runs, so it
  is NOT invisible to the inliner. The product rows below carry explicit
  style="" attributes for a different reason — THIS example builds with
  `inline_css: false` (see the CSS INLINING CONSTRAINT section below), so
  no per-tag styles are inlined for anything in this document, and the
  rows have to style themselves.

  TWO MORE REAL QUIRKS THIS EXAMPLE HAD TO WORK AROUND, found empirically
  while building it — all worth knowing if you hit unexplained diffs
  between your own Order A/B outputs:

  1. {%- for product in products -%} / {%- endfor -%} use Twig's explicit
     whitespace-control dashes, and the loop body is written densely (no
     stray blank lines). Without the dashes, indentation written around
     those two tags leaks into the loop body's own leading/trailing text
     once Twig expands it, and — because Order A normalizes whitespace
     AFTER Twig has expanded the loop into 3 rows, while Order B normalizes
     the ONE-row shell BEFORE Twig ever duplicates it — that leakage isn't
     cleaned up the same way in both orders. The dashes make the loop
     body's own whitespace fully explicit instead of relying on default
     trimming heuristics.

  2. Even with that, inky's pipeline-level cleanup (break_long_lines /
     collapse_closing_tags in inky-core's pipeline.rs) inserts or folds
     newlines around every <table>/<tbody>/<tr>/<td>/<th> tag it finds,
     unconditionally, in whatever document is in front of it at the moment
     it runs. Order A runs that cleanup on the FULLY-EXPANDED 3-row
     document; Order B runs it ONCE on the 1-row shell, and Twig's later
     per-recipient duplication has no further inky pass to reconcile the
     seams between copies. The visible symptom is a whitespace-only
     difference in the padding directly between table tags at row
     boundaries — never in the rows' actual content. run.php's equality
     check normalizes exactly that (and only that) before comparing — see
     the comment there for why that's principled and not a cop-out.

  CSS INLINING CONSTRAINT — both builds (Order A and Order B) must use
  `inline_css: false`. CSS inlining runs a separate HTML5 parse over inky's
  component-transform output. At shell-build time (Order B), the <raw>-
  wrapped loop remains literal {% for %}/{% endfor %} text sitting beside a
  <tr> inside <tbody>. That second parse's foster-parenting rules relocate
  bare template text out of the table, the same failure mode that <raw>
  prevents during the first parse. Setting `inline_css: false` sidesteps the
  second parse entirely, keeping both orders byte-comparable (framework_css
  still ships the compiled theme as a <style> block). See run.php's comment
  for the full detail. This constraint does not apply to templates that
  merge all data before inky runs (see 09-transactional, which uses
  `inline_css: true`).

  Inky's OWN `data` option (see 03-data-merge, 09-transactional) speaks a
  MiniJinja dialect that is syntax-compatible with Twig for the simple
  cases used here — {{ var }}, {% if %}, {% for %} mean the same thing to
  both engines. Reach for `data` alone when a template only needs that.
  Reach for real Twig, as here, when you need something a CMS's own Twig
  environment already provides that `data` can't: filters, functions,
  macros, template inheritance. The `loyalty_badge` filter below
  (registered in PHP, in run.php) is a genuinely Twig-only feature — inky's
  `data` merge has no mechanism for user-registered filters at all.
#}
<layout src="../../shared/layout.html" title="This week at Northwind Coffee">
<link rel="stylesheet" href="../../shared/themes/northwind.scss">
<container>
  <row>
    <column lg="12">
      <h1>Hey {{ subscriber.first_name }}, here's what's roasting</h1>
      <p>{{ subscriber.tier|loyalty_badge }} members get first pick of this
      week's small-batch arrivals before we open the list to everyone
      else.</p>
      <table role="presentation" width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
        <tr>
          <th align="left">New arrival</th>
          <th align="right">Price</th>
        </tr>
<raw>
{%- for product in products -%}
<tr>
<td style="padding:8px 0;">{{ product.name|upper }}</td>
<td align="right" style="padding:8px 0;">${{ product.price }}</td>
</tr>
{%- endfor -%}
</raw>
</table>
      <button href="{{ shop_url }}">Shop this week's arrivals</button>
    </column>
  </row>
</container>
